Introduction ¶

Phase 1 Summary ¶

The project aims to predict diabetes in female patients of Pima Indian Heritage within 5 years of the initial examination, using 8 diagnostic measurements (UCI Machine Learning, 2017). Phase 1 of the project started with data preprocessing where unusual values and missing values were found in variable Glucose, Blood_Pressure, Skin_Thickness, Insulin, and BMI, so median imputation was performed for those variables. Then, data visualisation was were generated for Phase 1. Upon exploring Phase 1 visualisation, we found moderate correlation between BMI and Skin_Thickness and Pregnancies and Age. Glucose and BMI are found to be moderately correlated with the outcome of diabetes prediction in the dataset. We observed skewness in some variables and found that patients who are diagnosed with diabetes within 5 years (Outcome = 1), tend to have higher values in descriptive variables than those who were not diabetic in 5 years, especially for their value of Glucose. Phase 1 report Table 1 found class imbalance in the target feature, where 268 patients were diagnosed with diabetes and 500 patients were not diagnosed with diabetes within 5 years of the examination.

At the end of Phase 1, we planned to perform scaling in Phase 2 to normalise data so it suits machine learning (ML) algorithms that we'll use for Phase 2. The diabetes dataset used for Phase 2 has been preprocessed in Phase 1 and saved with diabetes.to_csv("diabetesP1.csv", index=False).

Report Overview ¶

Following data preprocessing and visualisation in Phase 1, Phase 2 of the project aims to perform predictive modeling to predict whether a patient will have diabetes in 5 years, based on diagnostic measurements taken in the initial examination. Phase 2 will begin with an overview of the predictive modelling methodology, then moving on to: (1) perform data scaling, (2) select the best descriptive features with visualisation, (3) hyper-parameter fine-tuning and performance analysis of each ML algorithm with visualisation, and (4) compare performance of ML algorithms. In the end, we will discuss critique and limitations of the approach, and provide summary and conclusions of findings and the project.

Overview of Methodology ¶

Phase 2 will use the following classifiers to predict the target feature:

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
  • Decision Trees (DT)
  • Random Forest (RF)

KNN is similarity-based learning. It uses the distance between data points to determine the nearest neighbors, and classifies new data points based on their similarities to those neighbors. DT is information-based learning. It uses the most informative to split the dataset with respect to the target feature value. RF is an ensemble method that multiple DTs are combined with bagging and subspace sampling and makes predictions by returning the majority vote.

In the Predictive Modeling section, we will first perform scaling on descriptive features to transform data to a range between 0 and 1. For DT and RF, scaling ensures that features with larger scales such as Insulin are not overpowering during splitting, making sure all descriptive features have equal contribution. For KNN, scaling ensures that distance calculation is not biased due to features having different scales.

We will then perform feature selection using Random Forest Importance (RFI) and spFSR. RFI is filter-based. It calculates the average decrease in node impurities (measured by Gini index)from splitting on a particular feature over all decision trees in the ensemble. spFSR uses binary stochastic approximation to select the best features that's suitable for each classifier used. For feature selection in in Phase 2 we use spFSR as a filter so it is not bound by the specific classifier.

Model fitting and fine-tuning is the next step in predictive modeling, where we tune the hyperparameters of KNN, DT and RF to find the optimal hyperparameters for each ML algorithms to be use on the diabetes dataset, using cross-validation.

Lastly, we compare the performance of KNN, DT, and RF based on different metrics such as cross-validation, visualisation of ROC curve, accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report. A combination of paired t-test and visual inspection will be used to determine the best model to be used to predict the presence of diabetes in patients.

Feature Selection (FS) ¶

Since the diabetes dataset only has 768 observations, we use cross-validation instead of the hold-out method for the small dataset, also to avoid the lucky split. As outlined in our methodology, we use RFI and spFSR to select the best features, and compare the results of cross-validation between the full model, and models with features selected by RFI and spFSR methods, and we will do so for each ML algorithm (KNN, DT and RF).

The cross-validation method used is a stratified 5-fold cross-validation with 3 repetitions. As class imbalance exists in the diabetes dataset, we use stratification to make sure the proportion of each Outcome (diagnosed or not diagnosed with diabetes) in both train and test sets remain the same as full dataset in each cross-validation repetition.

For scoring metric, we set it to roc_auc because it is insensitive to class imbalance. Also, we want to optimize the model's performance on identifying positive cases to diagnose the presence of diabetes in patients.

In [7]:
cv_method = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, 
                                     n_repeats=3,
                                     random_state=999)
scoring_metric = 'roc_auc'

To recap, cv results from RFI method are:

  • KNN:0.786

cv results from full models are:

  • KNN:0.79

Compared with cv results from RFI and spFSR method, the full models for DT and RF seem to perform better than those with selected 5 features. But for KNN, cv result from spFSR method with 5 features is best with 0.794, compared to 0.786 with RFI with 5 features, and 0.79 with the full model.

To determine if the differences are statistically significant, we perform paired t-test below. If the p-value is smaller than 0.05, we conclude that the difference is statistically significant at 95% significance level.

In [28]:
#RFI vs. spFSR
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_rfi_knn, cv_results_spfsr_knn).pvalue.round(3))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_rfi_dt, cv_results_spfsr_dt).pvalue.round(3))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_rfi_rf, cv_results_spfsr_rf).pvalue.round(3))

Model Fitting & Tuning ¶

We split data into into 70:30 train and test sets to prevent over-fitting. We will use the train set for model fitting and fine-tuning of hyperparameters, and the test sets for model comparison.

As specified in Phase 1 summary, due to the uneven proportion of classes in the target feature, we set the stratify = target to mitigate the impact of class imbalance.

We continue to use cv method and scoring metric set in the Feature Selection stage.

In [34]:
#split data into train and test sets
D_train, D_test, t_train, t_test = \
    train_test_split(Data, target, test_size = 0.3, 
                     stratify=target, shuffle=True, random_state=999)

DT¶

We set parameters to be fine-tuned criterion, max_depth and min_samples_split. criterion determines whether the Gini impurity index or information gain (entropy) is used to measure quality of split. max_depth controls maximum depth of the tree. min_samples_split sets the minimum number of samples required to split at a node.

A DF classifier is set using random_state=999 and used for grid search.

In [44]:
df_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=999)

params_dt = {'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
             'max_depth': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8],
             'min_samples_split': [2, 3]}

gs_dt = GridSearchCV(estimator=df_classifier, 
                     param_grid=params_dt, 
                     cv=cv_method,
                     n_jobs=-2,
                     verbose=1, 
                     scoring=scoring_metric)

gs_dt.fit(D_train, t_train);

The optimal criterion is found to be entropy with a maximum depth of 4 and minimum number of samples required to split at a node set to 2.

We found best test score to be 0.7768.

RF¶

First, we set parameters to be fine-tuned. n_estimators specifies number of decision trees in the forest. criterion determines whether the Gini impurity index or information gain (entropy) is used to measure quality of split. max_depth controls maximum depth of each tree in the forest. min_samples_split sets the minimum number of samples required to split at a node in each decision tree. class_weight is used to address class imbalance in the dataset.

A RF classifier is set using random_state=999 and used for grid search.

In [50]:
rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=999)

params_rf = {'n_estimators': [10, 50, 100, 200, 400],  
            'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
            'max_depth': [None, 5, 10],  
            'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],  
            'class_weight': ['balanced', 'balanced_subsample']}

gs_rf = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf_classifier,
                    param_grid=params_rf,
                    cv=cv_method,
                    n_jobs=-2,
                    verbose=1,
                    scoring=scoring_metric)

gs_rf.fit(D_train, t_train);

After training, we found the optimal is to have 200 trees in the forest, use entropy, set no maximum depth of each tree in the random forest, set minimum 10 samples to split at a node in each decision tree, and to apply weights to different classes per-tree. The best score for RF is 0.8322.

Critique & Limitations ¶

My approach to Phase 2 of the project has its strength and limitations.

Strengths¶

Phase 2 of this project acknowledged and dealt with imbalanced class in the diabetes dataset. I have tried to mitigate the effect of class imbalance on model performance in various ways, such as the use of roc_auc, and stratification. Various evaluation metrics were used to compare the performance of KNN, DT and RF models after hyperparameter fine-tuning. A combination of visual inspection and statistical test on evaluation metrics allows me to evaluate more comprehensively and mitigate bias of using one evaluation metric. Also, the model used were simple, therefore requiring less computational time to perform.

Limitations¶

A major limitation of this project is insufficient data. The diabetes dataset has only 768 observations and 8 descriptive variables. The small dataset limits the model's ability to generalize towards new data. One way to mitigate this limitation is to collect more data and using them the train the model. Data quality is also an issue with the diabetes dataset. Phase 1 of the project found missing values for 5 descriptive variables. Due to the small dataset size, we could not drop observations with missing value and had to impute with median values, which led to large outliers in those variables. Having a larger dataset could mitigate this issue. Also, better domain knowledge of diagnostic measurements might help with data preprocessing, as we might find a better value than median to impute the data with.

Another issue with the project is the lack of more complex and interpretable machine learning algorithms. All 3 models fitted for the project are simple models and might not be able to capture more complex patterns underlying in the data, and could lead to underfitting. We could try to fine-tune more hyperparameters to improve performance of existing models. Employing algorithms such as Neural Networks might also mitigate this issue, however it is limited by the performance of my laptop.

Summary & Conclusions ¶

Project Summary ¶

The project has 2 phases.

Phase 1 of the project covered data cleaning, data preprocessing, data visualisation and exploration. For initial data observation, we found unusual values and missing values in variable Glucose, Blood_Pressure, Skin_Thickness, Insulin, and BMI, and impute with median values. We then inspected further on all variables to make sure the dataset was clean and moved on to data visualisation and exploration. Class imbalance was found for the target feature with 268 patients diagnosed with diabetes and 500 patients not diagnosed with diabetes within 5 years of the examination. From visualisations, we found moderate correlations between variables such as BMI and Skin_Thickness, and observed differences in descriptive variable values between two classes of the Outcome variable. The difference is most evident in variable Glucose, which is later confirmed to be the most important feature in Phase 2.

In Phase 2, we performed predictive modeling using 3 machine learning algorithms, K Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Decision Tree (DT) and Random Forest (RF). After an overview of methodology, we imported clean data saved after Phase 1, and split the dataset into descriptive features and the target feature. We performed scaling on descriptive features to transform data to better suit the algorithms used.

Then we used Random Forest Importance (RFI) and spFSR to select the 5 best features, and compared them with models with full features, to see if performance increases with less features. With paired t-test, we found that the difference in performance between models with 5 features and full models are not statistically significant, and proceeded to the next section with full features. To mitigate the impact of class imbalance in the data, we used stratified 5-fold cross-validation with 3 repetitions and roc_auc as scoring metric.

For model fitting and fine-tuning, the dataset is split into train set and test set. The train set was use for this section and the test set is saved for model evaluation when comparing model performance after fine-tuning of hyperparameters. We fine-tuned the hyperparameters of KNN, DT and RF to find the optimal hyperparameters for each ML algorithms to be use on the diabetes dataset, using cross-validation.

Then, we compare the performance of KNN, DT, and RF with their optimal hyperparameters using various metrics such as cross-validation, ROC curve, accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report. We used paired t-test and visual inspection of evaluation metrics, and the RF model was found to be the best model for this project overall.

Summary of Findings ¶

From the diabetes dataset, we found Glucose, BMI, Pregnancies, and Age of more importance among measurements of 8 risk factors for diabetes in an examination. Researchers and medical professionals should pay more attention to these measurements during health check-up or screenings to better detect the presence of diabetes.

We found the optimal model using Random Forest, with 200 trees, no maximum depth of each tree in the random forest using the entropy criterion. The RF model sets minimum 10 samples to split at a node in each decision tree, apply weights to different classes per-tree to address class imbalance in the data. The optimal RF model has 78.8% accuracy and 74.4% true positive rate (recall) at predicting diabetes in females of Pima Indian heritage after 5 years of the initial examination.

Conclusions ¶

Prevalence of diabetes is higher for the population of Pima Indian Heritage compared to other ethnicities. The RF model found in this project could be used to assist detection of diabetes from their' health check-up data, or to be used to predict other diseases and conditions for early prevention and intervention to save lives and medicare costs.

We need sufficient data to train and test algorithms to better predict the presence of diabetes. Therefore, stakeholders and data scientists should work together to generate better models for detection, prevention and intervention of diabetes and other diseases.
